CXMOD — Connection eXperience MODule
=====================================
v2.1.1 | Apache-2.0 - developed under Alcapacit.

WHAT IT IS
----------
CXMOD is a compiled C system utility for Linux server network management.
Like iproute2 or ethtool, it reads directly from /proc and /sys — no Python,
no Ruby, no daemons, no runtime dependencies. A single statically-compilable
binary you deploy to any Linux system.

It diagnoses and fixes the networking bottlenecks that ship misconfigured in
every stock Linux installation:

  Problem                         Default Impact           CXMOD Fix
  ─────────────────────────────── ──────────────────────   ──────────────────────
  TCP buffer undersizing          Caps 1G @ 17 Mbit/s      tune --profile=*
  conntrack table overflow        Silent packet drops       conntrack --fix
  IRQ imbalance (all on CPU 0)    Single-CPU bottleneck     irq --balance
  TIME_WAIT accumulation          Port starvation           tune (tw_reuse)
  SYN backlog too small           Drops on traffic spikes   tune (max_syn_backlog)
  Orphan socket accumulation      OOM kills                 sockstat + tune
  IP fragmentation buildup        MTU mismatch drops        sockstat (diagnose)
  LRO on bridges/routers          HOL blocking              offload --fix-lro
  Settings reset on reboot        Manual work every boot    persist --profile=*
  No unified diagnostics          Blind to all of above     diagnose / fix


QUICK START
-----------
    tar -xzf CXMOD.tar.gz && cd cxmod
    make
    sudo ./cx fix              # Diagnose and fix everything automatically

    # Or preview before applying:
    sudo ./cx fix --dry-run    # Print every command first
    sudo ./cx diagnose         # Full health check (47+ checks)

    # Install system-wide:
    sudo make install             # /usr/local/sbin/cxmod + man page


BUILD
-----
Requirements:
  - GCC or Clang with C99 support
  - Linux kernel 3.10+ (RHEL 7 / Ubuntu 14.04 or newer)
  - GNU make
  Optional: ethtool (for offload subcommand)
  Optional: iproute2 tc (for QoS subcommand)

Build options:
  make                            Build the binary
  make check                      Run 35+ self-tests
  make install                    Install to /usr/local/sbin/
  make install PREFIX=/usr        Install to /usr/sbin/
  make dist                       Create CXMOD.tar.gz
  make deb                        Build .deb package (requires dpkg-deb)
  make rpm                        Build .rpm package (requires rpmbuild)

Configure script (optional — checks for compiler and tools):
  ./configure --prefix=/usr/local
  make


SUBCOMMANDS
-----------
DIAGNOSTICS & REPAIR
  cx diagnose                           Full health check (47+ checks)
  cx fix [--dry-run]                    Fix everything in one shot
  cx report [--json] [--output=FILE]   Diagnostic report file

TUNING PROFILES
  cx tune --profile=balanced            General-purpose servers
  cx tune --profile=high_throughput     Bulk transfers, CDN, file servers
  cx tune --profile=low_latency         VoIP, gaming, interactive SSH
  cx tune --profile=satellite           High-RTT WAN, satellite links
  cx tune --profile=hardened            Security-hardened servers
  cx tune --list                        Show all profiles
  cx tune --bdp 10000 20               BDP calculator (10Gbit, 20ms RTT)
  cx tune --auto-bdp                    Auto-detect from NIC speed
  cx tune --set KEY=VALUE              Set individual sysctl
  cx tune --current                     Show current kernel values

PERSISTENCE (survives reboots)
  cx persist --profile=balanced        Write to /etc/sysctl.d/90-cxmod.conf
  cx persist --show                     Show saved configuration
  cx persist --remove                   Remove saved configuration

CONNECTION TRACKING
  cx conntrack                          Table usage and timeouts
  cx conntrack --states                 TCP connection state breakdown
  cx conntrack --fix                    Scale table, fix timeouts

IRQ & PACKET STEERING
  cx irq [--iface=IF]                  NIC IRQ distribution
  cx irq --balance [--iface=IF]        Distribute IRQs round-robin
  cx irq --rps [--iface=IF]            Enable RPS/XPS

NIC OFFLOAD (requires ethtool)
  cx offload [--iface=IF]              Show TSO/GSO/GRO/LRO status
  cx offload --fix-lro                 Disable LRO on all interfaces
  cx offload --set FEAT on|off         Toggle offload feature

QOS TRAFFIC SHAPING (requires tc/iproute2)
  cx qos --apply --iface=IF --bw=M    Apply 4-class HTB QoS
  cx qos --remove --iface=IF           Remove QoS
  cx qos --show [--iface=IF]           Show active qdiscs

ROUTING
  cx route                              Show routing table
  cx route --add DST [via GW] [dev IF]
  cx route --del DST

STATISTICS
  cx proto                              Protocol stats (/proc/net/snmp)
  cx sockstat                           Socket & buffer pressure
  cx iface [--iface=IF]                Interface statistics
  cx monitor [--iface=IF] [--interval=ms]   Live throughput


PROFILE DETAILS
---------------
balanced (default, safe for all servers):
  rmem/wmem_max:         32 MiB    (was 4 MiB — leaves 1G link at 17%)
  somaxconn:             4096      (was 128 — drops connections under load)
  tcp_tw_reuse:          1         (was 0 — TIME_WAIT exhausts ports)
  tcp_fin_timeout:       30s       (was 60s — stale sockets linger)
  tcp_syncookies:        1         (SYN flood protection)
  tcp_ecn:               1         (congestion signaling)
  ip_local_port_range:   10240-65535  (55k ephemeral ports)

high_throughput (CDN, file servers, bulk transfer):
  rmem/wmem_max:         128 MiB   (for 10G * 100ms BDP)
  congestion_control:    bbr       (delay-based vs loss-based)
  somaxconn:             65535     (high connection rate)

satellite (high-RTT WAN, intercontinental):
  rmem/wmem_max:         256 MiB   (for 100Mbit * 600ms BDP)
  congestion_control:    bbr
  tcp_slow_start_after_idle: 0

hardened (DMZ, public-facing, security):
  tcp_timestamps:        0         (reduces fingerprinting)
  tcp_fastopen:          0         (reduces attack surface)
  rp_filter:             1         (strict reverse-path filtering)
  icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts: 1   (smurf protection)


DESIGN DECISIONS
----------------
- Zero runtime dependencies: no libpcap, no libnetfilter, no Python
- Reads /proc and /sys directly: same as ss(8), ip(8), ethtool(8)
- C99 standard: compiles on RHEL 7+ (GCC 4.8+) through RHEL 10
- -Wall -Wextra -Wpedantic: zero warnings in production build
- Handles missing kernel features gracefully
- All sysctl writes are atomic: safe on live production systems
- --dry-run available for every operation that changes kernel state


